Can You Find Light in the Darkness?

The world is full of light from sources like the Sun, a bulb, or a computer screen. It bounces off objects, and some of it finds its way into your eyes. This is how visual information about the world enters your vision system.

Between bounces, light usually travels in straight lines called rays. This fact is hardwired into your brain, and it's how you form a mental picture of the world around you from an image.

What exactly happens when a ray of light hits an object's surface?

The exact answer depends on the kind of surface in question, but in general two things can happen:

  • Light can be absorbed. The ray ends its journey, slightly warming up the surface with the energy it carries.

  • Light can be reflected. It bounces off the surface and starts going in a new direction.

Some surfaces, such as smoothly polished metal, reflect almost all light that lands on them in a special way known as specular reflection. (The word 'specular' just means 'mirror-like'.) Light rays that hit a mirror are traveling in one direction before the collision and in a different direction afterwards. These directions obey a simple relationship.

Let's follow a ray of light coming in toward a mirror at an angle. To figure out which direction it's heading after it's reflected, we draw a line that is perpendicular to the mirror's surface, which is called the normal to the surface. The angle between this ray of light and the normal is called the angle of incidence. If the angle is zero, the ray is coming in perpendicular to the mirror; if the angle is 90°\ang{90}90°, then the ray is going along the surface of the mirror, just grazing it.

After bouncing off the mirror, the reflected ray always makes the same angle with the normal as the incoming ray. This is often stated as the 'law of reflection':

Law of reflection: The angle of incidence is equal to the angle of reflection.

Light reflecting in a mirror looks exactly the same as if there is a light on the far side of the mirror, shining through. It's as if there is another world that has been reflected through the mirror plane. We can see how this follows from the law of reflection:

Objects in the imaginary 'reflected' world are known as the 'images' of objects in the real world. If there are multiple mirrors, a ray can reflect several times, creating an image of an image of an image...

To solve problems involving reflection, we often start by following light backwards, starting with the eye. If a ray comes to our eye in a particular direction, we can trace it back to see where it came from. If we trace it back to a mirror, we know a ray must have hit the mirror in a direction given by the law of reflection. Eventually, we will come to a light source.

For example, imagine we're looking into a box through a very narrow eyepiece which only allows rays through in one direction. Inside the box are three lights which emit red, green, and blue lights. Which light will we see when we look through the eyepiece?

ray length{\color{#333333}\text{ray length}}ray length

We can follow a ray of light backwards, starting at the eyepiece. The ray came from a mirror at an angle of 45°\ang{45}45° from the normal. Another ray must have hit this mirror at 45°\ang{45}45° since the angle of reflection equals the angle of incidence, and we can follow this ray back to the light source. Alternatively, we can draw a reflected image of the inside of the box and follow the ray through the mirror into the image.

In this case, if we follow the ray back far enough, we meet a green light, so we will see a green light if we look through the eyepiece.
